              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section id="overview">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-title">
          <h2>Project Overview</h2>
          <p>
            Automatic modulation classification identifies the modulation type of a received RF signal without requiring prior transmitter information. This project studies how a CNN can learn modulation features directly from noisy I/Q waveform data.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid-3">
          <article class="card">
            <div class="icon">01</div>
            <h3>Problem</h3>
            <p>
              Traditional AMC methods depend on handcrafted signal features and often degrade when the channel has low signal-to-noise ratio.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <div class="icon">02</div>
            <h3>Approach</h3>
            <p>
              A CNN is trained on raw I/Q samples so the model can learn amplitude, phase, and waveform patterns automatically.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <div class="icon">03</div>
            <h3>Goal</h3>
            <p>
              Evaluate classification accuracy across SNR levels and identify where the model struggles under noisy channel conditions.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="method">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-title">
          <h2>Methodology</h2>
          <p>
            The project pipeline moves from raw RF signal data to preprocessing, CNN feature extraction, and final modulation classification.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="workflow">
          <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">1</span>
            <h3>I/Q Data</h3>
            <p>Each signal sample contains in-phase and quadrature components that preserve amplitude and phase information.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">2</span>
            <h3>Preprocessing</h3>
            <p>Signals are formatted, normalized, labeled, and split into training, validation, and testing groups.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">3</span>
            <h3>CNN Model</h3>
            <p>Convolutional filters learn waveform features such as phase transitions, amplitude changes, and modulation-specific structure.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">4</span>
            <h3>Output Class</h3>
            <p>A Softmax layer predicts the most likely modulation type from the learned feature representation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="grid-2" style="margin-top: 18px;">
          <article class="card">
            <h3>CNN Architecture</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Convolutional layers for automatic feature extraction</li>
              <li>ReLU activation for nonlinear signal relationships</li>
              <li>Max pooling for dimensionality reduction</li>
              <li>Dropout to reduce overfitting</li>
              <li>Fully connected layer for classification</li>
              <li>Softmax output for class probability</li>
            </ul>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>Training Setup</h3>
            <table class="data-table">
              <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Value</th></tr>
              <tr><td>Optimizer</td><td>Adam</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Loss Function</td><td>Cross-Entropy</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Batch Size</td><td>64 or 128</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Epochs</td><td>20–50</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Input Shape</td><td>128 × 2</td></tr>
            </table>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="dataset">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-title">
          <h2>Dataset</h2>
          <p>
            The model is evaluated using RadioML-style I/Q signal data with multiple modulation schemes and a wide range of channel noise levels.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid-2">
          <article class="card">
            <h3>Signal Representation</h3>
            <p>
              Each sample is represented as a two-channel time-series signal. The I component captures the in-phase part of the waveform, while the Q component captures the quadrature part. Together, they describe the signal's amplitude and phase behavior.
            </p>
            <div class="tag-list">
              <span class="tag">Raw I/Q samples</span>
              <span class="tag">128 time points</span>
              <span class="tag">2 channels</span>
              <span class="tag">Amplitude + phase</span>
            </div>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>Modulation Classes</h3>
            <p>
              The project focuses on common modulation schemes used in digital communication systems. Similar classes become harder to separate when noise increases.
            </p>
            <div class="tag-list">
              <span class="tag">BPSK</span>
              <span class="tag">QPSK</span>
              <span class="tag">8PSK</span>
              <span class="tag">16QAM</span>
              <span class="tag">64QAM</span>
            </div>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="results">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-title">
          <h2>Results and Analysis</h2>
          <p>
            Accuracy improves as SNR increases. At low SNR, noise hides the signal structure and makes similar modulation types harder to distinguish.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid-2">
          <article class="card">
            <h3>Accuracy vs. SNR</h3>
            <div class="chart" aria-label="Accuracy by SNR level">
              <div class="bar-row"><span>-20 dB</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 12%;"></div></div><span>12%</span></div>
              <div class="bar-row"><span>-15 dB</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 18%;"></div></div><span>18%</span></div>
              <div class="bar-row"><span>-10 dB</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 28%;"></div></div><span>28%</span></div>
              <div class="bar-row"><span>-5 dB</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 45%;"></div></div><span>45%</span></div>
              <div class="bar-row"><span>0 dB</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 72%;"></div></div><span>72%</span></div>
              <div class="bar-row"><span>5 dB</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 80%;"></div></div><span>80%</span></div>
              <div class="bar-row"><span>10 dB</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 88%;"></div></div><span>88%</span></div>
              <div class="bar-row"><span>15 dB</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 92%;"></div></div><span>92%</span></div>
              <div class="bar-row"><span>18 dB</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 95%;"></div></div><span>95%</span></div>
            </div>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>Key Findings</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Low SNR strongly reduces classification accuracy.</li>
              <li>Accuracy increases as the received signal becomes cleaner.</li>
              <li>QPSK and 8PSK are harder to separate because they are both phase-based.</li>
              <li>16QAM and 64QAM are harder to separate because their constellation structures overlap more under noise.</li>
              <li>Hyperparameter tuning is important for avoiding overfitting.</li>
            </ul>
          </article>
        </div>

        <article class="card" style="margin-top: 18px;">
          <h3>Confusion Matrix Example</h3>
          <table class="matrix" aria-label="Confusion matrix">
            <tr>
              <th>Actual \ Predicted</th>
              <th>BPSK</th>
              <th>QPSK</th>
              <th>8PSK</th>
              <th>16QAM</th>
              <th>64QAM</th>
            </tr>
            <tr><th>BPSK</th><td class="diag">96</td><td>2</td><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>0</td></tr>
            <tr><th>QPSK</th><td>2</td><td class="diag">93</td><td>3</td><td>1</td><td>1</td></tr>
            <tr><th>8PSK</th><td>1</td><td>3</td><td class="diag">93</td><td>2</td><td>1</td></tr>
            <tr><th>16QAM</th><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>2</td><td class="diag">94</td><td>2</td></tr>
            <tr><th>64QAM</th><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>2</td><td>2</td><td class="diag">94</td></tr>
          </table>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="impact">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-title">
          <h2>Why This Matters</h2>
          <p>
            RF signal classification is useful when a receiver needs to identify unknown signals in noisy or changing wireless environments.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid-3">
          <article class="card">
            <h3>Cognitive Radio</h3>
            <p>AMC helps radios understand what type of signal is present so communication systems can adapt to the spectrum environment.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card">
            <h3>Spectrum Awareness</h3>
            <p>Classifying unknown signals supports monitoring, signal intelligence, and better awareness of crowded RF environments.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card">
            <h3>Noise Robustness</h3>
            <p>Testing performance across SNR values shows where a model is reliable and where stronger architectures may be needed.</p>
